Recent Changes to Improve Safety



The Oil City Plant performs periodic process hazard analyses (safety reviews) of all chemical processes, including the isobutylene system. Some of the recently completed changes to improve the safety of the isobutylene storage and transfer system are listed below.



1)Isobutylene thermal expansion relief valves located at the storage vessels and the unloading area were piped to the flare system instead of to atmosphere;



2)Isobutylene railcar unloading connections were changed to inherently safer dry-lock fittings;



3)Internal excess flow valves were installed in the storage vessels on the primary liquid and vapor transfer nozzles;



4)External excess flow valves and  leak-free thermometer thermowells were installed on small vessel appurtenances on the storage vessels;



5)Additional LEL detection systems with shutdown interlocks were installed in pipe rack locations that contain isobutylene piping;



6)Several process area fixed fire extinguishing systems were interlocked to shut down isobutylene equipm

ent in the event of fire system activation;



7)Hot work procedures were upgraded to include continuous LEL monitoring during all hot work performed in Hazardous Locations;



8)Hazardous Locations were re-evaluated for proper electrical classifications and all electrical equipment for these areas was confirmed to be compliant;



9)A Building Siting Study was conducted by an external consultant and several corrective action items were implemented based on the findings; and



10)Layer of Protection Analyses (LOPAs) were performed on critical equipment within the Isobutylene system and additional layers of protection have been added where the analyses did not meet the specified risk criteria.



The Oil City Plant has a continuous improvement philosophy in all safety and environment issues.
